 to the places the bard once lived with the help of contemporary Scottish Gaelic poets and scholars. Through investigation and imagination, Bowering forms a connection with MacLeod despite vast differences of culture and language, time and place. Their connection deepens as Bowering twines MacLeod’s story with accounts of the people and places that shaped her own life, a connection that ultimately reveals the foundations of Bowering’s artistic vocation to herself.MacLeod’s life and writing, little known today beyond the Gaelic world, harbours cultural truths about a transformative era of war and colonization in Gaelic Scotland. Bringing a poetic sensibility to investigative scholarship, More Richly in Earth offers a profound reflection on the necessity of art in all forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPoets, Scottishy17th centuryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh  a17th century.  aAngus Peter Campbell.  aAonghas MacNeacail.  aAtlantic rescues.  aCorryvreckan.  aCulloden.  aDunvegan.  aGaelic poetry.  aHebrides.  aIona Statues.  aJacobite.  aMeg Bateman.  aMinch.  aMyles Campbell.  aNewfoundland disasters.  aRodel.  aScottish female poets.  aSir Norman MacLeod.  aSt Clements.  aSwallow.  aWorld War 1.  acolonisation.  aexile.  aface down burial.  apoetry foremothers.  awomen bards.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311140848440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228021674?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228021674423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228021674/original  a978-3-11-140848-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles